var SIE_QUESTIONS_SERIES66 = [{"id":"series66-s66-q-018","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"REIT dividends are generally taxed as:","choices":{"A":"Qualified dividends at preferential rates","B":"Ordinary income","C":"Long-term capital gains","D":"Tax-exempt income"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Unlike qualified dividends from corporations, REIT dividends are taxed as ordinary income because REITs don't pay corporate-level taxes. The qualified dividend rate doesn't apply.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["reits"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-042","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under SEC rules, an investment adviser may charge performance-based fees to a client who:","choices":{"A":"Has any amount invested with the adviser","B":"Has at least $500,000 in assets under management","C":"Has at least $1.1 million invested with the adviser","D":"Is over 65 years old"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SEC allows performance-based fees for \"qualified clients\" which includes individuals with at least $1.1 million in assets under management with the adviser, or a net worth exceeding $2.2 million (excluding primary residence). These thresholds are adjusted periodically for inflation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-120","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which retirement account is subject to required minimum distributions (RMDs) during the owner's lifetime?","choices":{"A":"Roth IRA","B":"Roth 401(k)","C":"Neither Roth IRA nor Roth 401(k)","D":"Both Roth IRA and Roth 401(k)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Roth 401(k) accounts are subject to RMDs during the owner's lifetime, unlike Roth IRAs which have no RMDs while the owner is alive. However, Roth 401(k) funds can be rolled into a Roth IRA to avoid RMDs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-122","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser wants to charge performance-based (fulcrum) fees to a client. What qualification must the client meet?","choices":{"A":"Net worth of at least $500,000","B":"Assets under management of at least $1.1 million OR net worth of at least $2.2 million","C":"Annual income of at least $200,000","D":"At least 5 years of investment experience"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under SEC and NASAA rules, performance-based fees (fulcrum fees) can only be charged to qualified clients, defined as having at least $1.1 million in assets under management with the adviser OR a net worth of at least $2.2 million (excluding primary residence).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-151","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"When a customer opens an options account, the firm must verify certain information on the options agreement. Which of the following is NOT typically verified by the firm?","choices":{"A":"Annual income","B":"Employment status","C":"Number of dependents","D":"Investment experience"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When verifying an options agreement, firms typically verify financial information such as income, net worth, investment experience, and employment status. The number of dependents, like marital status, is not a standard verification item for options account approval.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv2","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent learns of a promising investment opportunity from a college roommate who runs a tech startup. The agent provides written notification to the firm, negotiates a finder's fee, and solicits several clients. The agent has acted:","choices":{"A":"Ethically, since written notification was provided","B":"Ethically, since the finder's fee shows transparency","C":"Unethically, by soliciting clients without proper authorization","D":"Unethically, by failing to obtain written approval from the firm"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Providing written notification is not sufficient. An agent must obtain written APPROVAL from the broker-dealer before participating in any private securities transaction (selling away). Written notification alone does not authorize the activity, and accepting finder's fees without firm approval is also a violation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-152","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"Three NASDAQ market makers display the following quotes for XYZ stock: Market Maker A: 45.10/45.25, Market Maker B: 45.15/45.30, Market Maker C: 45.12/45.22. What is the inside market?","choices":{"A":"$45.10/$45.30","B":"$45.12/$45.25","C":"$45.15/$45.22","D":"$45.10/$45.22"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The inside market represents the best bid (highest) and best ask (lowest) from all market makers. The highest bid is $45.15 (Market Maker B), and the lowest ask is $45.22 (Market Maker C). Therefore, the inside market is $45.15/$45.22.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["market-makers","secondary-market"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv6","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent recommends a thinly-traded security that pays an above-average commission. Before executing the trade, the agent fully discloses to the client that the security is illiquid and that the commission is substantially higher than typical. The agent has:","choices":{"A":"Acted unethically by recommending an illiquid security","B":"Acted unethically due to the high commission","C":"Acted ethically by providing full disclosure","D":"Violated the USA prohibition on excess commissions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Full and fair disclosure of material facts, including illiquidity and commission amounts, satisfies the agent's ethical obligations. The client can then make an informed decision. Higher commissions are not prohibited if properly disclosed and the recommendation is suitable.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv8","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under NASAA model rules, which of the following is a prohibited practice for a registered agent?","choices":{"A":"Recommending securities consistent with client objectives","B":"Providing written disclosure of conflicts of interest","C":"Participating in private securities transactions without firm approval","D":"Executing unsolicited client orders"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Selling away (participating in private securities transactions without broker-dealer approval) is a prohibited practice under NASAA model rules and the Uniform Securities Act. Agents must obtain written approval before engaging in any outside business activities involving securities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv11","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser representative is terminating employment. Which form is NOT used to withdraw their registration?","choices":{"A":"Form ADV-W","B":"Form U6","C":"Form U5","D":"Form BD-W"},"answer":"B","explanation":"There is no Form U6 in the securities industry registration system. Form U5 is used to terminate an agent's registration, Form ADV-W is used to withdraw an investment adviser's registration, and Form BD-W withdraws a broker-dealer's registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv12","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A personal trainer refers clients to a broker-dealer and receives a referral fee for each client who opens an account and makes trades. The personal trainer:","choices":{"A":"May receive referral fees without registration","B":"Must register as an agent to receive transaction-based compensation","C":"Is exempt from registration as a professional","D":"May receive fees if under $500 per referral"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Receiving transaction-based compensation (commissions, referral fees tied to trades) for securities activities requires registration as an agent. The personal trainer is engaging in activities requiring registration and cannot receive such fees without proper licensing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv15","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, who has primary authority to enforce state securities laws and regulations?","choices":{"A":"The SEC","B":"FINRA","C":"The Federal Reserve","D":"The State Administrator"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The Uniform Securities Act grants the State Administrator (also called Securities Commissioner in some states) the authority to administer and enforce state securities laws, including registration, investigation, and enforcement actions within the state.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["state-regulators","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv19","section":"Regulatory Bodies","stem":"What form do broker-dealers use for ongoing financial reporting to regulators?","choices":{"A":"Form ADV","B":"Form U4","C":"Form BD","D":"FOCUS Report"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Broker-dealers file FOCUS (Financial and Operational Combined Uniform Single) Reports for ongoing financial condition reporting to FINRA and the SEC. Form BD is for initial registration, Form ADV is for investment advisers, and Form U4 is for individual registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv21","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent's Form U4 must be amended within 30 days for which of the following events?","choices":{"A":"A written customer complaint alleging unauthorized trading","B":"A verbal complaint resolved within 24 hours","C":"A customer inquiry about account fees","D":"A routine address change inquiry"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Written customer complaints alleging sales practice violations, such as unauthorized trading, must be reported on an amended Form U4 within 30 days. Verbal complaints, routine inquiries, and minor matters do not trigger U4 amendment requirements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-165","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which statements about margin account disclosure requirements are TRUE? I. Interest charges must be disclosed. II. Risks of margin must be explained. III. Maintenance requirements must be stated. IV. Margin calls are never required.","choices":{"A":"I only","B":"I and II only","C":"I, II, and III only","D":"I, II, III, and IV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Margin account disclosures must include interest charges (I), margin risks (II), and maintenance requirements (III). Statement IV is false - margin calls ARE required when equity falls below maintenance levels.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["margin-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv51","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, which of the following are included in the definition of a broker-dealer? I. A firm that effects securities transactions for others for compensation. II. A bank that sells certificates of deposit. III. A firm engaged in the business of buying and selling securities for its own account.","choices":{"A":"I and III only","B":"I and II only","C":"II and III only","D":"I, II, and III"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, a broker-dealer is defined as any person engaged in the business of effecting transactions in securities for the accounts of others (broker) or for its own account (dealer). Banks are specifically excluded from the broker-dealer definition when engaging in traditional banking activities like selling CDs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv53","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"A tombstone advertisement for a new securities offering may include all of the following information EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"The total dollar amount of proceeds to be received by the issuer","B":"The name of the issuer","C":"The type of security being offered","D":"Where a prospectus may be obtained"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Tombstone advertisements are limited to basic information and cannot include the gross or net proceeds to the issuer. They may only contain the issuer name, type of security, offering price, and where to obtain a prospectus. Any additional details would constitute an illegal prospectus.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv58","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Form BD requires disclosure of all of the following EXCEPT:","choices":{"A":"Criminal history of control persons","B":"Names of associated persons","C":"Detailed financial information about controlling partners' personal assets","D":"Regulatory actions against the firm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Form BD requires disclosure of control persons, criminal and regulatory history, and business information, but it does not require detailed personal financial information about controlling partners. The form focuses on identifying and background information, not personal wealth details.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-202","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The internal rate of return (IRR) is best defined as:","choices":{"A":"The average annual return of an investment","B":"The total return divided by the holding period","C":"The discount rate at which the present value of future cash flows equals the initial investment","D":"The risk-adjusted return relative to benchmark performance"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The internal rate of return (IRR) is the discount rate that makes the net present value (NPV) of all cash flows equal to zero, or equivalently, the rate at which the present value of future cash flows equals the initial investment. It represents the compound rate of return earned on invested capital.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv76","section":"Economics","stem":"An investor wants to know how long it will take to double her money if she earns a 12% annual return. Using the Rule of 72, the answer is approximately:","choices":{"A":"4 years","B":"6 years","C":"8 years","D":"12 years"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Rule of 72 provides a quick estimate for doubling time: 72 divided by the interest rate equals years to double. At 12% annual return: 72 / 12 = 6 years. This shortcut is useful for quick mental calculations.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["interest-rates"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv77","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A fulcrum fee arrangement, where an adviser's fee may increase or decrease based on performance relative to a benchmark, may ONLY be offered to which type of client?","choices":{"A":"Qualified clients","B":"Accredited investors","C":"Retail customers","D":"Any client who agrees in writing"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Under the Investment Advisers Act, performance-based fees including fulcrum fees may only be charged to qualified clients. A qualified client generally has at least $1.1 million under management with the adviser or a net worth exceeding $2.2 million. This protects less sophisticated investors from potentially abusive fee structures.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv78","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The SEC's Regulation Best Interest (Reg BI) establishes four key obligations for broker-dealers when making recommendations to retail customers. These four obligations are:","choices":{"A":"Suitability, documentation, supervision, compliance","B":"Due diligence, fair dealing, disclosure, compensation","C":"Disclosure, care, conflict of interest, compliance","D":"Know your customer, best execution, fair pricing, disclosure"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Regulation BI requires broker-dealers to satisfy four component obligations: (1) Disclosure - provide material facts about the recommendation and relationship; (2) Care - exercise reasonable diligence, care, and skill; (3) Conflict of Interest - establish policies to identify and mitigate conflicts; (4) Compliance - establish written policies and procedures.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["reg-bi"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv79","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An affiliate of an issuer holds unregistered shares under SEC Rule 144. When selling these shares in the open market, the affiliate is subject to:","choices":{"A":"A complete prohibition on sales","B":"Both holding period and volume limitations","C":"Volume limitations only","D":"Holding period requirements only"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Affiliates (control persons) holding shares are always subject to volume limitations under Rule 144, regardless of how long they have held the shares. The volume limit is the greater of 1% of outstanding shares or average weekly trading volume. Since the question specifies the shares are already held, only volume limitations apply to the sale.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv80","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under state law, which of the following organizations does NOT have access to non-public information about registered persons without prior approval?","choices":{"A":"FINRA","B":"SEC","C":"State securities administrators","D":"NAPFA"},"answer":"D","explanation":"NAPFA (National Association of Personal Financial Advisors) is a private professional association, not a regulatory body. Unlike FINRA, the SEC, and state administrators who have regulatory authority to access non-public information, NAPFA has no such authority and would require approval to access confidential regulatory information.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv81","section":"State Regulations","stem":"State anti-fraud provisions of the Uniform Securities Act apply to the offer and sale of securities. These provisions do NOT apply to:","choices":{"A":"Securities sold through private placements","B":"Exempt securities such as municipal bonds","C":"Securities sold by unregistered agents","D":"Items excluded from the definition of a security"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Anti-fraud provisions apply to ALL securities transactions, including exempt securities and exempt transactions. However, if something is entirely excluded from the definition of a security (such as commodities, fixed annuities, or whole life insurance), the securities anti-fraud rules simply do not apply because no security is involved.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv82","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A customer calls their broker and states, \"Buy me 100 shares of XYZ stock sometime today when you think the price is right.\" This type of instruction:","choices":{"A":"Does not require a power of attorney because the customer initiated the order","B":"Requires a power of attorney because the broker has price discretion","C":"Requires a written authorization for time discretion","D":"Is prohibited under FINRA rules"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Time and price discretion does not require a power of attorney when the customer initiates the order on the same day. The customer has specified the security and quantity; the broker is merely determining the optimal execution time and price. Discretion over which securities to buy or how many shares would require authorization.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv83","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An investment adviser who strongly believes in the Efficient Market Hypothesis (EMH) would most likely consider which type of analysis to be least useful in generating excess returns?","choices":{"A":"Technical analysis using charts and price patterns","B":"Fundamental analysis of financial statements","C":"Economic analysis of GDP growth","D":"Diversification across asset classes"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Efficient Market Hypothesis states that all available information is already reflected in stock prices. Technical analysis, which attempts to predict future prices based on past price patterns and trading volume, would be considered useless under EMH because historical prices are already incorporated. Even weak-form EMH suggests technical analysis cannot provide an edge.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv84","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"During the cooling-off period for a new securities offering, which of the following activities is permitted?","choices":{"A":"Accepting purchase orders from customers","B":"Confirming sales of the new securities","C":"Soliciting indications of interest from potential investors","D":"Sending the final prospectus to customers"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During the 20-day cooling-off period (between filing and effective date), issuers and underwriters may distribute preliminary prospectuses (red herrings) and solicit indications of interest. No sales can be made, no orders accepted, and no money collected until the registration becomes effective. Indications of interest are non-binding expressions of potential interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["securities-act-1933","primary-market"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv85","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which of the following is NOT typically considered an advantage of investing in mutual funds compared to individual securities?","choices":{"A":"Contingent deferred sales charges (CDSCs)","B":"Professional management","C":"Diversification","D":"Convenience and record-keeping"},"answer":"A","explanation":"CDSCs (back-end loads) are fees charged when investors sell mutual fund shares, typically declining over time. This is a cost and potential disadvantage, not an advantage. Professional management, diversification, and administrative convenience are genuine benefits of mutual funds over selecting individual stocks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv86","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A portfolio manager seeking stocks that are more volatile than the overall market should look for securities with:","choices":{"A":"Beta greater than 1.0","B":"Beta less than 1.0","C":"Beta equal to 1.0","D":"Negative beta"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Beta measures a security's volatility relative to the market. A beta greater than 1.0 indicates the security is more volatile than the market (e.g., beta of 1.5 means 50% more volatile). Beta of 1.0 equals market volatility, below 1.0 is less volatile, and negative beta moves opposite to the market.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv87","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A broker-dealer has existing clients who have moved to a new state where the BD is not currently registered. To continue servicing these clients, which of the following is required?","choices":{"A":"Only the broker-dealer must register in the new state","B":"Both the broker-dealer and any agents serving those clients must register","C":"Only the agents must register in the new state","D":"No registration is required for existing clients"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When clients move to a new state, both the broker-dealer and the agents serving those clients must register in that state to continue servicing them. The Uniform Securities Act requires registration in any state where business is conducted. There is typically a 30-day de minimis exemption for incidental existing clients, but continued service requires full registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv88","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Hedge fund managers are typically compensated through which fee structure?","choices":{"A":"A percentage of assets under management plus a percentage of capital gains","B":"A flat annual fee regardless of performance","C":"Commission on each transaction executed","D":"Hourly fees for consultation services"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Hedge funds typically use a \"2 and 20\" fee structure: 2% of assets under management (AUM) annually, plus 20% of profits (capital gains/performance fees). This structure aligns manager interests with investors but can result in substantial fees. Performance fees can only be charged to qualified clients.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv89","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which of the following is NOT typically a benefit of investing in a fund of hedge funds compared to a single hedge fund?","choices":{"A":"Diversification across multiple managers and strategies","B":"Lower overall fees","C":"Professional selection and monitoring of hedge funds","D":"Lower minimum investment requirements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Fund of hedge funds actually have HIGHER fees, not lower, due to the additional layer of management. Investors pay fees to the fund of funds manager on top of the underlying hedge fund fees (creating a \"double layer\" of fees). Benefits include diversification, professional manager selection, and typically lower minimums than investing in individual hedge funds directly.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv90","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio has the following annual returns over five years: 8%, 12%, 14%, 18%, and 5%. What is the median return?","choices":{"A":"11.40%","B":"12.00%","C":"13.00%","D":"14.00%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To find the median, first arrange the values in order: 5%, 8%, 12%, 14%, 18%. With five values, the median is the middle value (third value). The median return is 12.00%. The mean (average) would be 11.4%, but the question asks for median.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv91","section":"Economics","stem":"An investment grows from $850,000 to $3,400,000 over 12 years. The approximate compound annual growth rate is closest to:","choices":{"A":"8.00%","B":"10.00%","C":"11.00%","D":"12.00%"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The investment quadrupled (grew 4x) in 12 years. Using the Rule of 72: to double takes about 6 years at 12% (72/12=6), and doubling twice (quadrupling) takes 12 years. Alternatively, the exact CAGR formula gives approximately 12.25%, closest to 12.00%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["interest-rates"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv92","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which of the following is NOT a principle of Modern Portfolio Theory (MPT)?","choices":{"A":"Diversification can reduce portfolio risk","B":"Adding highly correlated assets improves the efficient frontier","C":"Investors should focus on portfolio risk, not individual security risk","D":"There is a trade-off between expected return and risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Modern Portfolio Theory emphasizes adding assets with LOW correlation to reduce overall portfolio risk. Adding highly correlated assets would NOT improve the efficient frontier and contradicts MPT principles. MPT focuses on diversification benefits from combining assets that don't move together.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv93","section":"Options","stem":"When opening an options account for a new customer, which document must be provided FIRST?","choices":{"A":"Options Disclosure Document (ODD)","B":"Options agreement","C":"Margin agreement","D":"Risk acknowledgment form"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Options Disclosure Document (ODD), also known as \"Characteristics and Risks of Standardized Options,\" must be delivered to the customer at or before the time the account is approved for options trading. The options agreement can be signed later (within 15 days of account approval). The ODD ensures customers understand options risks before trading.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["options-strategies","customer-documentation"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv94","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"When comparing actively managed mutual funds to passively managed index funds, which statement is most accurate?","choices":{"A":"Active funds consistently outperform passive funds","B":"Active funds have lower portfolio turnover","C":"Passive funds guarantee positive returns","D":"Passive funds typically have lower expense ratios"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Passively managed index funds typically have significantly lower expense ratios than actively managed funds because they don't require extensive research teams or frequent trading. Active funds have higher turnover and fees. Studies show most active funds underperform their benchmarks over time, partly due to higher costs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds","etfs"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv95","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under the Dodd-Frank Act provisions affecting investment adviser registration, which of the following statements are TRUE? I. Mid-sized advisers may register with the SEC or state. II. Small advisers must register with the state. III. Large advisers (over $110 million AUM) must register with the SEC. IV. Advisers to private funds may have different thresholds.","choices":{"A":"I and II only","B":"II and III only","C":"I, II, and III only","D":"I, III, and IV only"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Under Dodd-Frank: (I) Mid-sized advisers ($25-110 million AUM) have flexibility; (III) Large advisers over $110 million generally must register with the SEC; (IV) Private fund advisers have special provisions. Statement II is incorrect as stated - small advisers must register with their state, but there are exemptions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv96","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A self-employed individual takes an early distribution from their HR-10 (Keogh) plan at age 52. The distribution will be subject to:","choices":{"A":"Ordinary income tax plus a 10% early withdrawal penalty","B":"Capital gains tax only","C":"No tax if rolled over within 90 days","D":"State tax only"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Early distributions from HR-10 (Keogh) plans before age 59.5 are subject to ordinary income tax (since contributions were tax-deductible) PLUS a 10% early withdrawal penalty. The rollover window is 60 days, not 90 days. This treatment is similar to traditional IRAs and other qualified retirement plans.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv97","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Using the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), calculate the expected return for a stock with a beta of 1.25, given a risk-free rate of 3% and an expected market return of 9.4%.","choices":{"A":"9.40%","B":"11.00%","C":"12.75%","D":"14.75%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"CAPM formula: Expected Return = Risk-Free Rate + Beta x (Market Return - Risk-Free Rate). Expected Return = 3% + 1.25 x (9.4% - 3%) = 3% + 1.25 x 6.4% = 3% + 8% = 11.00%. The market risk premium (9.4% - 3% = 6.4%) is multiplied by beta to determine the risk premium for this specific stock.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv98","section":"Trading Securities","stem":"A customer places a sell stop-limit order at 78 with a limit of 77.50 when a stock is trading at $80. The stock drops rapidly through the following prices: $79, $78.10, $77.25, $77.50. At what price, if any, could this order be executed?","choices":{"A":"$79.00","B":"$78.10","C":"$77.50","D":"The order would not be executed"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A sell stop-limit order becomes a limit order when the stop price ($78) is reached. Once triggered at or below $78, it can only execute at $77.50 or better (higher). When the stock hits $78.10, the stop is triggered and the order could fill at $78.10 since it's above the $77.50 limit. At $77.25, no execution since it's below the limit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["order-types"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv99","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A security that is neither registered nor exempt may still be legally sold in a state if the transaction is:","choices":{"A":"Made through a registered broker-dealer","B":"Disclosed in writing to the customer","C":"An unsolicited order from the customer","D":"Approved by the state administrator"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, unsolicited transactions are an exempt transaction, allowing unregistered non-exempt securities to be sold legally. If the customer initiates the transaction without any solicitation from the agent, the transaction qualifies for this exemption. The agent must document that the order was truly unsolicited.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-qb-s66-pv100","section":"Economics","stem":"A tax system where individuals with higher incomes pay a higher percentage of their income in taxes is known as a:","choices":{"A":"Regressive tax","B":"Flat tax","C":"Progressive tax","D":"Proportional tax"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A progressive tax system charges higher tax rates to those with higher incomes. The U.S. federal income tax is progressive with marginal tax brackets (10%, 12%, 22%, 24%, 32%, 35%, 37%). A regressive tax takes a higher percentage from lower-income earners (like sales tax). A flat/proportional tax charges the same rate regardless of income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiscal-policy"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-001","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A stock trades at $50 with EPS of $2.50. What is the P/E ratio?","choices":{"A":"10","B":"15","C":"20","D":"25"},"answer":"C","explanation":"P/E = Price / EPS = $50 / $2.50 = 20. The stock trades at 20 times earnings, which is in the average range for most stocks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-002","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which type of company would typically have a HIGH P/E ratio and LOW dividend yield?","choices":{"A":"A utility company","B":"A growth technology company","C":"A value-oriented bank","D":"A mature consumer staples company"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Growth companies (like technology firms) typically have high P/E ratios because investors expect future earnings growth. They reinvest profits rather than paying dividends, resulting in low or no dividend yields.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-003","section":"Risk Return","stem":"A company has a price-to-book ratio of 0.8. This most likely indicates:","choices":{"A":"The stock is significantly overvalued","B":"The stock is trading below its book value and may be undervalued","C":"The company has strong earnings growth","D":"The company pays high dividends"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A P/B ratio below 1.0 means the stock is trading below its book value (accounting value of assets minus liabilities). This may indicate the stock is undervalued, though it could also signal financial distress.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-004","section":"Economics","stem":"Using the Rule of 72, approximately how long will it take to double an investment earning 6% annually?","choices":{"A":"6 years","B":"9 years","C":"12 years","D":"15 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Using the Rule of 72: 72 / 6 = 12 years to double the investment. This quick calculation helps estimate compound growth.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["interest-rates"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-005","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An investment has a Net Present Value (NPV) of -$5,000. The investment adviser should recommend:","choices":{"A":"Accepting the investment because any NPV is acceptable","B":"Rejecting the investment because it destroys value","C":"Accepting if the IRR is positive","D":"Additional analysis before making any recommendation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A negative NPV means the present value of future cash flows is less than the initial investment cost. The investment destroys value and should be rejected.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-006","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"For a bond, the Internal Rate of Return (IRR) is equal to:","choices":{"A":"The coupon rate","B":"The current yield","C":"The yield to maturity (YTM)","D":"The dividend yield"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A bond's IRR equals its yield to maturity (YTM). YTM represents the total return an investor will receive if the bond is held until maturity, accounting for both coupon payments and any gain or loss from buying at a premium or discount.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-008","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which measure indicates that a portfolio manager has outperformed expectations based on the level of risk taken?","choices":{"A":"High beta","B":"Positive alpha","C":"High standard deviation","D":"Low Sharpe ratio"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Alpha measures excess return compared to what beta would predict. Positive alpha indicates the manager generated returns above what would be expected for the risk level (outperformance). High beta just means more volatility, not outperformance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-009","section":"Risk Return","stem":"Standard deviation measures which type of risk?","choices":{"A":"Systematic risk only","B":"Unsystematic risk only","C":"Total risk (both systematic and unsystematic)","D":"Credit risk only"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Standard deviation measures TOTAL risk — the combination of systematic (market) risk and unsystematic (company-specific) risk. Beta, by contrast, measures only systematic risk. This distinction frequently appears on the exam.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk","unsystematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch1-010","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The Sharpe ratio uses which of the following in its denominator?","choices":{"A":"Beta","B":"Alpha","C":"Standard deviation","D":"Variance"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Sharpe ratio formula is (Return - Risk-Free Rate) / Standard Deviation. It measures excess return per unit of TOTAL risk (standard deviation). A higher Sharpe ratio indicates better risk-adjusted performance.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-001","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is covered by FDIC insurance?","choices":{"A":"Money market mutual funds","B":"Money market deposit accounts","C":"U.S. Treasury bills","D":"Corporate bonds held at a brokerage"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Money market DEPOSIT accounts are bank products covered by FDIC insurance. Money market MUTUAL FUNDS are securities and are NOT FDIC insured. Treasury bills and corporate bonds are also not bank deposits and are not FDIC insured.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-002","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Commercial paper typically has a maximum maturity of:","choices":{"A":"90 days","B":"180 days","C":"270 days","D":"365 days"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Commercial paper maturities are limited to 270 days to avoid SEC registration requirements. Commercial paper is unsecured corporate debt used to finance short-term obligations.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-003","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Treasury bills differ from Treasury notes and bonds in that T-Bills:","choices":{"A":"Are not backed by the U.S. government","B":"Pay interest semiannually","C":"Are sold at a discount and mature at par value","D":"Are subject to state and local taxes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"T-Bills are sold at a discount to face value and mature at par (face value). They do not pay periodic interest like T-Notes and T-Bonds. The difference between purchase price and par value is the investor's return.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-004","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"If interest rates rise, what happens to existing bond prices?","choices":{"A":"Prices rise","B":"Prices fall","C":"Prices stay the same","D":"It depends on the bond's maturity"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bond prices and interest rates have an INVERSE relationship. When market interest rates rise, existing bonds with lower coupon rates become less attractive, causing their prices to fall. This is one of the most important concepts in fixed income.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-005","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond with a 5% coupon is trading at 104. This bond is trading at:","choices":{"A":"A discount because the coupon is low","B":"Par value","C":"A premium because the price exceeds par","D":"Cannot be determined without knowing market rates"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A quote of 104 means the bond trades at 104% of par value, or $1,040 for a $1,000 par bond. Since the price exceeds par ($1,000), the bond trades at a premium. This occurs when the coupon rate exceeds current market rates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-006","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"For a bond trading at a premium, which yield would be the LOWEST?","choices":{"A":"Nominal yield","B":"Current yield","C":"Yield to maturity","D":"Yield to call"},"answer":"D","explanation":"For premium bonds, yields from lowest to highest are: YTC < YTM < Current Yield < Nominal Yield. YTC is lowest because the investor loses the premium faster if called early.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["bond-yields"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-007","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A $1,000 par bond with a 6% coupon is trading at $900. What is the current yield?","choices":{"A":"5.4%","B":"6.0%","C":"6.67%","D":"7.5%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Current Yield = Annual Coupon / Market Price = $60 / $900 = 6.67%. The current yield is higher than the 6% coupon rate because the bond trades at a discount.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-yields"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-008","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor in the 30% tax bracket is considering a municipal bond yielding 4%. What is the tax-equivalent yield?","choices":{"A":"4.00%","B":"4.57%","C":"5.71%","D":"6.00%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax-Equivalent Yield = Muni Yield / (1 - Tax Rate) = 4% / (1 - 0.30) = 4% / 0.70 = 5.71%. A taxable bond would need to yield at least 5.71% to match the after-tax return.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-009","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE about Treasury securities?","choices":{"A":"Interest is exempt from federal taxes","B":"Interest is exempt from state and local taxes","C":"They are backed by specific government projects","D":"They carry significant default risk"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Treasury interest is federally taxable but EXEMPT from state and local taxes. Treasuries are backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government, making them essentially free of default risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-010","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A corporate bond rated BB would be classified as:","choices":{"A":"Investment grade","B":"High yield (junk)","C":"Prime quality","D":"Government-backed"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Corporate bonds rated BB or below are classified as \"high yield\" or \"junk\" bonds. Investment grade bonds are rated BBB/Baa or higher. High yield bonds offer greater yields but carry significantly more credit risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["corporate-bonds","bond-ratings"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-011","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which government agency's securities are backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government?","choices":{"A":"Fannie Mae (FNMA)","B":"Freddie Mac (FHLMC)","C":"Ginnie Mae (GNMA)","D":"All of the above"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Only GNMA (Ginnie Mae) securities are explicitly backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. government. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac have only an implicit guarantee, making their securities slightly riskier (and offering slightly higher yields).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["government-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-013","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Zero-coupon bonds have NO:","choices":{"A":"Interest rate risk","B":"Credit risk","C":"Reinvestment risk","D":"Inflation risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Zero-coupon bonds have NO reinvestment risk because there are no periodic interest payments to reinvest. However, they have the HIGHEST interest rate risk because all cash flow is received at maturity, making them highly sensitive to rate changes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["corporate-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-014","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"A bond has a duration of 7 years. If interest rates rise by 1%, the bond's price will approximately:","choices":{"A":"Rise by 7%","B":"Fall by 7%","C":"Rise by 1%","D":"Fall by 1%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Using the duration formula: Price Change = -Duration x Rate Change = -7 x 1% = -7%. When rates rise, prices fall. A duration of 7 means the bond price will fall approximately 7% for each 1% rise in rates.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch2-015","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"Which risk increases with SHORTER bond maturities?","choices":{"A":"Interest rate risk","B":"Credit risk","C":"Reinvestment risk","D":"Inflation risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Reinvestment risk increases with shorter maturities because investors must reinvest principal (and any coupons) more frequently, potentially at lower rates. Interest rate risk, by contrast, increases with LONGER maturities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["bond-pricing"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-001","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor owns 100 shares of XYZ stock at $60 per share. After a 3-for-1 stock split, the investor will have:","choices":{"A":"33 shares at $180","B":"100 shares at $60","C":"300 shares at $20","D":"300 shares at $60"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a 3-for-1 split, shares triple (100 x 3 = 300) and price is divided by 3 ($60 / 3 = $20). Total value stays the same: $6,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-002","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which voting method most benefits minority shareholders?","choices":{"A":"Statutory voting","B":"Cumulative voting","C":"Proxy voting","D":"Majority voting"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Cumulative voting allows shareholders to concentrate all their votes on a single director candidate, helping minority shareholders elect at least one representative to the board.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-003","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"To receive a declared cash dividend, an investor must purchase the stock:","choices":{"A":"On or before the declaration date","B":"Before the ex-dividend date","C":"On or before the record date","D":"Before the payment date"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To receive a dividend, an investor must buy BEFORE the ex-dividend date. The ex-date is 1 business day before the record date, allowing time for T+1 settlement.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-004","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"In a corporate bankruptcy, common stockholders are paid:","choices":{"A":"First, because they are the owners","B":"After secured creditors but before unsecured creditors","C":"After preferred stockholders but before bondholders","D":"Last, after all creditors and preferred stockholders"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Common stockholders have the lowest priority (residual claims) and are paid last in bankruptcy. The order is: secured creditors, unsecured creditors, subordinated debt, preferred stock, then common stock.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-005","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A company has 6% cumulative preferred stock with $100 par value. If dividends were skipped for 2 years, how much must be paid per share before common stockholders can receive dividends?","choices":{"A":"$6 (current year only)","B":"$12 (2 years of arrears)","C":"$18 (arrears plus current year)","D":"$24 (2 years of arrears times 2)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For cumulative preferred: Annual dividend = $100 x 6% = $6. Arrears (2 years) = $12. Plus current year = $6. Total = $18 must be paid before any common dividends.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-006","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"An investor owns $100 par convertible preferred stock with a conversion ratio of 5:1. The preferred stock is trading at $130 and the common stock is trading at $28. Should the investor convert?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because converting creates a $10 profit per share","B":"No, because the common stock value after conversion is only $140","C":"Yes, because the common parity is $26","D":"No, because the preferred stock is trading above par"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Converting 1 preferred share yields 5 common shares worth $28 x 5 = $140. The preferred is worth $130. Converting creates $140 - $130 = $10 profit per preferred share.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-007","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which type of preferred stock offers NO protection if dividends are missed?","choices":{"A":"Cumulative preferred","B":"Convertible preferred","C":"Non-cumulative preferred","D":"Participating preferred"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Non-cumulative preferred offers no protection for missed dividends. If the board skips a dividend, that payment is lost forever and cannot be recovered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-008","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"When would a company most likely call its preferred stock?","choices":{"A":"When interest rates rise","B":"When interest rates fall","C":"When the stock price falls","D":"When dividends are in arrears"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Companies call preferred stock when interest rates fall so they can reissue new preferred stock at a lower dividend rate, reducing their dividend expense.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["preferred-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-009","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"A stock currently pays a $3.00 dividend that is expected to grow 4% annually. If an investor requires a 10% return, what is the intrinsic value using the Gordon Growth Model?","choices":{"A":"$30.00","B":"$50.00","C":"$52.00","D":"$75.00"},"answer":"C","explanation":"D1 = $3.00 x 1.04 = $3.12. Value = $3.12 / (0.10 - 0.04) = $3.12 / 0.06 = $52.00. Remember to use next year's dividend (D1), not the current dividend.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-010","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which of the following would a technical analyst use?","choices":{"A":"Price-to-earnings ratio","B":"Moving averages and support levels","C":"Financial statements","D":"Dividend growth rate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Technical analysts use charts and indicators like moving averages, support/resistance levels, and volume. P/E ratios, financial statements, and dividend analysis are fundamental analysis tools.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-011","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"If a stock's calculated intrinsic value is $45 and its current market price is $55, the stock is:","choices":{"A":"Undervalued and should be bought","B":"Overvalued and should be sold","C":"Fairly valued and should be held","D":"Unable to be evaluated"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When intrinsic value ($45) is LESS than market price ($55), the stock is OVERVALUED. The market is paying more than the stock is calculated to be worth, suggesting a sell signal.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-012","section":"Equity Securities","stem":"Which statement best describes fundamental analysis versus technical analysis?","choices":{"A":"Fundamental determines when to buy; technical determines what to buy","B":"Fundamental determines what to buy; technical determines when to buy","C":"Both determine what to buy using different methods","D":"Both determine when to buy using different methods"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Fundamental analysis answers \"WHAT to buy\" by finding undervalued stocks through financial analysis. Technical analysis answers \"WHEN to buy\" by identifying optimal entry and exit points through price and volume patterns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["common-stock"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-013","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"In a firm commitment underwriting, who bears the risk if all shares are not sold?","choices":{"A":"The issuing company","B":"The underwriter","C":"The investors","D":"The SEC"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a firm commitment, the underwriter purchases all shares from the issuer and resells them to the public. If they cannot sell all shares, the underwriter bears the loss on unsold shares.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-014","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"During the cooling-off period, an underwriter may:","choices":{"A":"Accept orders and payment for shares","B":"Distribute the final prospectus","C":"Distribute the preliminary prospectus and take indications of interest","D":"Begin trading the securities on an exchange"},"answer":"C","explanation":"During the cooling-off period (SEC review), the underwriter can distribute the preliminary prospectus (red herring) and take non-binding indications of interest, but cannot accept money or make sales.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market","sec"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-015","section":"Capital Markets","stem":"A SPAC (Special Purpose Acquisition Company) is best described as:","choices":{"A":"A company with multiple business segments","B":"A shell company that raises funds to acquire a private company","C":"A type of mutual fund that invests in IPOs","D":"A private equity fund for accredited investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A SPAC is a \"blank check company\" - a shell company with no operations that raises money through an IPO with the purpose of acquiring a private company, allowing that target to become public without a traditional IPO.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["primary-market"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch3-016","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under Rule 144, the holding period for restricted securities of a reporting company is:","choices":{"A":"3 months","B":"6 months","C":"1 year","D":"2 years"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under Rule 144, the holding period for restricted securities is 6 months for SEC-reporting companies (those that file 10-K, 10-Q reports) and 1 year for non-reporting companies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["sec","securities-act-1933"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-001","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor places an order to buy mutual fund shares at 2:00 PM ET. At what price will the order be executed?","choices":{"A":"The NAV calculated at 2:00 PM","B":"The previous day's closing NAV","C":"The NAV calculated at 4:00 PM that day","D":"The average of the opening and closing NAV"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Mutual fund orders are executed at the NAV calculated after market close (4:00 PM ET) on the day the order is received. This is forward pricing. Orders received before 4:00 PM get that day's NAV.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-002","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which mutual fund share class is MOST suitable for an investor planning to invest $100,000 for 15 years?","choices":{"A":"Class A shares","B":"Class B shares","C":"Class C shares","D":"All classes are equally suitable"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Class A shares are best for long-term investors with large investments. The $100,000 investment qualifies for significant breakpoints, reducing the front-end load. The lower ongoing 12b-1 fees (0.25% vs. 1%) result in lower total costs over 15 years.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-003","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"What is the maximum 12b-1 fee a mutual fund can charge?","choices":{"A":"0.25%","B":"0.75%","C":"1.00%","D":"1.25%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The maximum 12b-1 fee is 1.00%, consisting of a 0.75% distribution fee and a 0.25% service fee. Funds charging more than 0.25% in 12b-1 fees cannot call themselves \"no-load\" funds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-004","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"An investor wants to invest $48,000 in a mutual fund where the $50,000 breakpoint reduces the sales charge from 5% to 4%. A representative should:","choices":{"A":"Process the order as requested at the 5% load","B":"Inform the investor about the breakpoint and suggest investing $50,000","C":"Recommend splitting the investment into two purchases","D":"Suggest Class C shares to avoid any sales charge"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Representatives must inform investors of available breakpoints. With only $2,000 more investment, the investor would save 1% on the entire purchase. Failing to disclose this is a breakpoint violation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-005","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which of the following is TRUE about ETFs?","choices":{"A":"They can only be purchased at NAV like mutual funds","B":"They trade throughout the day on exchanges at market prices","C":"They always trade at exactly NAV","D":"They cannot be sold short"},"answer":"B","explanation":"ETFs trade on exchanges throughout the trading day at market prices, which may be slightly above (premium) or below (discount) NAV. Unlike mutual funds, they can be traded anytime the market is open.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-006","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"What is the primary function of Authorized Participants in the ETF market?","choices":{"A":"To set the NAV of the ETF daily","B":"To keep ETF prices aligned with NAV through arbitrage","C":"To manage the underlying portfolio","D":"To approve new investors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Authorized Participants keep ETF prices close to NAV through the creation/redemption mechanism. When the ETF trades at a premium, they create new shares; when it trades at a discount, they redeem shares. This arbitrage keeps prices aligned.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-007","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"A leveraged 2x ETF is designed to:","choices":{"A":"Double the annual return of an index","B":"Double the daily return of an index","C":"Provide twice the dividend yield","D":"Hold twice as many securities as the index"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Leveraged ETFs are designed to deliver multiples of DAILY returns, not annual returns. Due to daily reset and compounding, long-term returns may differ significantly from the expected multiple. They should only be used for short-term trading.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-008","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which characteristic distinguishes a UIT from a mutual fund?","choices":{"A":"UITs trade on exchanges","B":"UITs have actively managed portfolios","C":"UITs have fixed portfolios and set maturity dates","D":"UITs can only hold bonds"},"answer":"C","explanation":"UITs have fixed portfolios that do not change after creation and have a set maturity date when the trust terminates. Mutual funds have no maturity date and their portfolios can change based on manager decisions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uits"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-009","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"How much of taxable income must a REIT distribute to shareholders to maintain its tax-advantaged status?","choices":{"A":"At least 50%","B":"At least 75%","C":"At least 90%","D":"Exactly 100%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"REITs must distribute at least 90% of their taxable income to shareholders to maintain their tax-advantaged status and avoid corporate-level taxation. Most distribute 100% to avoid any taxes at the entity level.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch4-012","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"A limited partner in a DPP invests $50,000. If the partnership incurs $200,000 in losses, the limited partner:","choices":{"A":"Is liable for their proportionate share of the $200,000","B":"Can lose a maximum of $50,000","C":"Is personally liable for all partnership debts","D":"Must contribute additional capital"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Limited partners' liability is limited to their investment amount. If a limited partner invests $50,000, that is the maximum they can lose, regardless of how much the partnership loses overall. General partners, not limited partners, have unlimited liability.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["mutual-funds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-001","section":"Annuities","stem":"Which life insurance product requires a securities license to sell?","choices":{"A":"Term life insurance","B":"Whole life insurance","C":"Universal life insurance","D":"Variable life insurance"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Variable life insurance is a security because the cash value is invested in a separate account tied to market performance. It requires both an insurance license AND a securities license (Series 6 or 7) to sell.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["variable-life"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-002","section":"Annuities","stem":"What distinguishes a separate account from a general account?","choices":{"A":"Separate accounts are only for term insurance","B":"General accounts expose policyholders to investment risk","C":"Separate accounts hold variable product cash values with investment risk on the policyholder","D":"Separate accounts are guaranteed by the insurance company"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Separate accounts hold the cash value of variable products, and the investment risk is borne by the policyholder. General accounts hold fixed product cash values, with investment risk on the insurance company and guaranteed returns.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-life","variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-003","section":"Life Insurance","stem":"Which life insurance product offers flexible premiums and guaranteed cash value growth?","choices":{"A":"Term life","B":"Whole life","C":"Universal life","D":"Variable life"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Universal life offers flexible premiums (can increase, decrease, or skip payments) with cash value that earns a current interest rate (not variable). Whole life has fixed premiums. Variable life has fixed premiums with market-based cash value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["universal-life"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-004","section":"Life Insurance","stem":"How are life insurance death benefits generally taxed to the beneficiary?","choices":{"A":"Taxed as ordinary income","B":"Taxed as capital gains","C":"Income tax-free","D":"Taxed at 15% flat rate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Life insurance death benefits are generally income tax-free to beneficiaries. However, they may be subject to estate taxes if the deceased owned the policy and the estate exceeds exemption limits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["life-policy-provisions"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-005","section":"Annuities","stem":"What is the tax treatment of earnings withdrawn from a non-qualified annuity before age 59 1/2?","choices":{"A":"Tax-free","B":"Taxed as capital gains only","C":"Taxed as ordinary income plus 10% penalty","D":"Taxed at 15% flat rate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Earnings from a non-qualified annuity are taxed as ordinary income. Withdrawals before age 59 1/2 also incur a 10% early withdrawal penalty on the taxable portion (earnings).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-006","section":"Annuities","stem":"Under LIFO taxation, which portion of an annuity is withdrawn first?","choices":{"A":"Principal (cost basis)","B":"Earnings (gains)","C":"Half principal, half earnings","D":"Contract owner chooses"},"answer":"B","explanation":"LIFO (Last In, First Out) means the last money to go in (earnings) comes out first. All earnings are withdrawn and taxed as ordinary income before any tax-free return of principal.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-007","section":"Annuities","stem":"Which annuity payout option provides the HIGHEST periodic payment?","choices":{"A":"Life with 10-year period certain","B":"Joint and survivor","C":"Life only (straight life)","D":"20-year period certain"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Life only (straight life) provides the highest periodic payment because the insurance company takes no risk of paying a beneficiary. Payments end at the annuitant's death with nothing going to heirs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch5-008","section":"Annuities","stem":"A variable annuity is considered a security because:","choices":{"A":"It is sold by insurance companies","B":"It provides a death benefit","C":"The cash value is invested in a separate account with market risk","D":"It offers tax-deferred growth"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Variable annuities are securities because the cash value is invested in a separate account (subaccounts) and the contract owner bears the investment risk based on market performance. This is different from fixed annuities where the insurance company bears the risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["variable-annuities"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-001","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which of the following qualifies an individual as an accredited investor?","choices":{"A":"Net worth of $1 million including primary residence","B":"Net worth of $1 million excluding primary residence","C":"Annual income of $150,000 for the past two years","D":"Holding a Series 63 license"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To qualify as an accredited investor based on net worth, an individual must have $1 million+ EXCLUDING the value of their primary residence. Alternatively, $200K income ($300K joint) for 2 years, or holding Series 7, 65, or 82 licenses also qualifies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-002","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"What is the typical hedge fund fee structure known as \"2 and 20\"?","choices":{"A":"2% sales load and 20% redemption fee","B":"2% management fee and 20% performance fee","C":"2% expense ratio and 20% front-end load","D":"2% of profits and 20% management fee"},"answer":"B","explanation":"\"2 and 20\" refers to a 2% annual management fee (on assets under management) and a 20% performance fee (on profits, often above a hurdle rate and subject to a high-water mark).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-003","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Which of the following is NOT typically a characteristic of hedge funds?","choices":{"A":"Use of leverage and short selling","B":"Daily liquidity like mutual funds","C":"High minimum investments","D":"Lock-up periods"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Hedge funds typically have limited liquidity with lock-up periods (often 1-3 years) and restricted redemption windows (quarterly or annually). They do NOT offer daily liquidity like mutual funds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-004","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"Digital assets like cryptocurrency are:","choices":{"A":"Insured by SIPC up to $500,000","B":"Insured by FDIC up to $250,000","C":"Not insured by SIPC or FDIC","D":"Guaranteed by the Federal Reserve"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Digital assets (cryptocurrency) are NOT insured by SIPC or FDIC. There is no government protection for losses from cryptocurrency investments. They are highly speculative investments.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-005","section":"Options","stem":"An investor buys a call option with a strike price of $50 for a premium of $3. What is the breakeven point?","choices":{"A":"$47","B":"$50","C":"$53","D":"$56"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Long call breakeven = Strike + Premium = $50 + $3 = $53. The stock must rise above $53 for the investor to profit on the position.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["call-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-006","section":"Options","stem":"A stock is trading at $48. A 50 put option has a premium of $5. What is the intrinsic value and time value?","choices":{"A":"Intrinsic: $0, Time: $5","B":"Intrinsic: $2, Time: $3","C":"Intrinsic: $5, Time: $0","D":"Intrinsic: $3, Time: $2"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Put intrinsic value = Strike - Stock Price = $50 - $48 = $2. Time value = Premium - Intrinsic = $5 - $2 = $3.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["put-options","options-pricing"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-007","section":"Options","stem":"What is the maximum loss for the writer of a naked call option?","choices":{"A":"The premium received","B":"The strike price","C":"The strike price minus the premium","D":"Theoretically unlimited"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A naked (uncovered) call writer has theoretically unlimited loss potential because there is no limit to how high the stock price could rise. The writer would have to buy shares at the market price to deliver at the lower strike price.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["call-options","options-strategies"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-010","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"What is the primary risk unique to ETNs that ETFs do not have?","choices":{"A":"Market risk","B":"Tracking error","C":"Credit risk of the issuer","D":"Liquidity risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ETNs are unsecured debt obligations of the issuing bank, so they carry credit risk - if the issuer defaults, ETN holders may lose their investment. ETFs own the underlying assets and don't have this credit risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-011","section":"Packaged Products","stem":"Which statement about leveraged ETFs is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"They are ideal for long-term retirement investing","B":"They eliminate market risk through leverage","C":"They reset daily which can cause returns to differ from expected multiples over time","D":"They guarantee double the annual returns of the index"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Leveraged ETFs reset daily, causing compounding effects that make long-term returns differ significantly from expected multiples. This \"volatility decay\" makes them unsuitable for long-term holding.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["etfs","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch6-012","section":"Alternative Investments","stem":"A viatical settlement involves:","choices":{"A":"Purchasing municipal bonds from local governments","B":"Purchasing life insurance policies from terminally ill individuals","C":"Converting variable annuities to fixed annuities","D":"Exchanging one mutual fund for another"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A viatical settlement is the purchase of a life insurance policy from a terminally ill person (life expectancy less than 2 years). The buyer pays a lump sum, becomes the beneficiary, pays premiums, and receives the death benefit.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-001","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A private foundation must distribute what minimum percentage of its investment assets annually?","choices":{"A":"3%","B":"4%","C":"5%","D":"10%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Private foundations must distribute at least 5% of their investment assets annually for charitable purposes to maintain their tax-exempt status.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-002","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which type of trust avoids BOTH probate AND estate taxes?","choices":{"A":"Revocable living trust","B":"Irrevocable trust","C":"Testamentary trust","D":"Both revocable and irrevocable trusts"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Irrevocable trusts avoid both probate and estate taxes because the grantor has permanently given up ownership of the assets. Revocable trusts avoid probate but NOT estate taxes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-003","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"The person who creates and funds a trust is called the:","choices":{"A":"Trustee","B":"Beneficiary","C":"Grantor","D":"Executor"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The grantor (also called settlor or trustor) is the person who creates and funds the trust. The trustee manages the trust, and beneficiaries receive the benefits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"For 2024, the federal estate tax exemption is:","choices":{"A":"$5.49 million","B":"$11.7 million","C":"$12.92 million","D":"$13.61 million"},"answer":"D","explanation":"For 2024, the federal estate tax exemption is $13.61 million per individual. Estates valued below this amount are not subject to federal estate taxes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-005","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which investment objective seeks the HIGHEST potential returns with the HIGHEST risk?","choices":{"A":"Preservation","B":"Income","C":"Growth","D":"Speculation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Speculation seeks maximum returns and accepts the highest level of risk, including potential total loss of principal. It is appropriate only for investors who can afford to lose their entire investment.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","know-your-customer"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-006","section":"Suitability","stem":"What is the difference between risk capacity and risk tolerance?","choices":{"A":"There is no difference; they are the same","B":"Risk capacity is financial ability; risk tolerance is emotional willingness","C":"Risk tolerance is financial ability; risk capacity is emotional willingness","D":"Risk capacity applies to institutions; risk tolerance applies to individuals"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Risk capacity is the financial ABILITY to withstand losses (based on income, net worth, time horizon). Risk tolerance is the emotional WILLINGNESS to accept risk (based on personality and past experience).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["know-your-customer","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-007","section":"Suitability","stem":"A client has a 5-year investment time horizon. This would be classified as:","choices":{"A":"Short-term","B":"Medium-term","C":"Long-term","D":"Ultra long-term"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Medium-term is typically defined as 3-10 years. Short-term is less than 3 years, and long-term is more than 10 years. A 5-year horizon falls in the medium-term category.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["know-your-customer","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch7-008","section":"Suitability","stem":"Loss aversion in behavioral finance refers to:","choices":{"A":"The fear of any investment risk","B":"The tendency to feel losses more strongly than equivalent gains","C":"Avoiding all investments with potential for loss","D":"Always selling when investments decline"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Loss aversion means the psychological pain of losing money is felt more intensely than the pleasure of gaining an equivalent amount. This can cause investors to sell too early to avoid losses or avoid taking necessary risks.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["know-your-customer","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-001","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which of the following risks can be eliminated through diversification?","choices":{"A":"Interest rate risk","B":"Market risk","C":"Business risk","D":"Inflation risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Business risk is unsystematic (company-specific) risk that can be diversified away. Interest rate, market, and inflation risks are systematic risks that affect all securities and cannot be diversified away.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","unsystematic-risk"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-002","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"To achieve the GREATEST diversification benefit, an investor should add assets with what correlation to existing holdings?","choices":{"A":"+1.0 (perfect positive)","B":"+0.5 (moderate positive)","C":"0 (no correlation)","D":"-1.0 (perfect negative)"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Perfect negative correlation (-1.0) provides the maximum diversification benefit. When one asset declines, the other rises proportionally, reducing overall portfolio volatility.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-003","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A stock has a beta of 1.5. If the market rises 10%, the stock would be expected to:","choices":{"A":"Rise 10%","B":"Rise 15%","C":"Rise 5%","D":"Fall 15%"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Beta measures sensitivity to market movements. A beta of 1.5 means the stock moves 1.5 times the market. If the market rises 10%, the stock is expected to rise 10% x 1.5 = 15%.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["systematic-risk","risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-004","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Using CAPM, if the risk-free rate is 2%, the market return is 9%, and a stock has a beta of 1.2, what is the expected return?","choices":{"A":"8.4%","B":"9.0%","C":"10.4%","D":"10.8%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"E(R) = Rf + Beta x (Rm - Rf) = 2% + 1.2 x (9% - 2%) = 2% + 1.2 x 7% = 2% + 8.4% = 10.4%","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-005","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of portfolio rebalancing?","choices":{"A":"Maximizing returns","B":"Minimizing taxes","C":"Maintaining the desired risk level","D":"Reducing transaction costs"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The primary purpose of rebalancing is to maintain the desired risk level by returning the portfolio to its target allocation. Market movements cause drift that changes the portfolio's risk profile.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-006","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which allocation strategy makes SHORT-TERM changes based on market conditions?","choices":{"A":"Strategic asset allocation","B":"Tactical asset allocation","C":"Dollar-cost averaging","D":"Passive indexing"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Tactical asset allocation makes short-term deviations from strategic targets to capitalize on market conditions. Strategic allocation is long-term and changes only when client circumstances change.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-007","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An investor using dollar-cost averaging will:","choices":{"A":"Buy the same number of shares each month","B":"Buy more shares when prices are high","C":"Buy more shares when prices are low","D":"Only invest when markets are rising"},"answer":"C","explanation":"With dollar-cost averaging, a fixed dollar amount buys MORE shares when prices are LOW and FEWER shares when prices are HIGH. This lowers the average cost per share over time.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-008","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"According to investment research, what is the MOST important factor in determining long-term portfolio returns?","choices":{"A":"Individual security selection","B":"Market timing","C":"Asset allocation","D":"Fund manager skill"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Studies show asset allocation is the most important factor in determining long-term portfolio returns, accounting for approximately 90% of return variability. Security selection and timing have much smaller impacts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-009","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio with a POSITIVE alpha has:","choices":{"A":"Higher risk than the market","B":"Returns below expectations","C":"Returns above expectations based on its risk","D":"No systematic risk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Positive alpha indicates the portfolio returned MORE than what was expected based on its level of risk (beta). It represents outperformance and suggests the manager added value.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-010","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"Which return measure should be used to compare portfolio MANAGERS?","choices":{"A":"Dollar-weighted return","B":"Time-weighted return","C":"Internal rate of return","D":"Total return"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Time-weighted return eliminates the effect of cash flows (deposits/withdrawals) that managers don't control. This provides a fair comparison of manager skill.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-011","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"The Sharpe ratio differs from the Treynor ratio in that Sharpe uses:","choices":{"A":"Beta instead of standard deviation","B":"Standard deviation instead of beta","C":"Alpha instead of excess return","D":"Market return instead of risk-free rate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sharpe ratio uses standard deviation (total risk) in the denominator, while Treynor uses beta (systematic risk only). Use Sharpe for entire portfolios, Treynor for well-diversified portfolios.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch8-012","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"An appropriate benchmark for a small-cap U.S. stock fund would be:","choices":{"A":"S&P 500","B":"Russell 2000","C":"MSCI EAFE","D":"Bloomberg Aggregate"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Russell 2000 is a small-cap index, matching the investment universe of a small-cap fund. The S&P 500 is large-cap, MSCI EAFE is international, and Bloomberg Aggregate is bonds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["risk-measures"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-001","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the maximum 401(k) employee deferral contribution for 2025 for someone age 45?","choices":{"A":"$7,000","B":"$23,000","C":"$23,500","D":"$31,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"For 2025, the employee deferral limit is $23,500 for those under age 50. Catch-up contributions of $7,500 are available starting at age 50.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-002","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under 3-year cliff vesting, an employee who leaves after 2 years receives what percentage of employer contributions?","choices":{"A":"0%","B":"33%","C":"67%","D":"100%"},"answer":"A","explanation":"With 3-year cliff vesting, employees must complete 3 full years of service to become vested. Leaving before 3 years means 0% of employer contributions are vested. It is all-or-nothing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-003","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"For someone born in 1960 or later, at what age must RMDs begin under SECURE 2.0?","choices":{"A":"70 1/2","B":"72","C":"73","D":"75"},"answer":"D","explanation":"SECURE 2.0 raised the RMD age to 75 for those born in 1960 or later (effective 2033). Those born 1951-1959 have an RMD age of 73.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-004","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which retirement plan does NOT have a 10% early withdrawal penalty?","choices":{"A":"401(k)","B":"403(b)","C":"457(b)","D":"Traditional IRA"},"answer":"C","explanation":"457(b) governmental plans do not have the 10% early withdrawal penalty. Distributions are subject to income tax but no additional penalty regardless of age.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A Roth IRA has been open for 6 years and the owner is age 55. A withdrawal of earnings would be:","choices":{"A":"Tax-free and penalty-free","B":"Taxable as ordinary income only","C":"Subject to 10% penalty only","D":"Subject to both income tax and 10% penalty"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Although the 5-year rule is met, the owner is only 55 (under 59 1/2) and doesn't meet another qualifying event. Earnings withdrawn would be subject to both income tax and the 10% early withdrawal penalty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-006","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the maximum SEP-IRA contribution for 2024?","choices":{"A":"$7,000","B":"$23,000","C":"$69,000","D":"$115,500"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SEP-IRA contribution limit is the lesser of 25% of compensation or $69,000 for 2024. Unlike 401(k) plans, SEP-IRAs allow only employer contributions, not employee deferrals.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-007","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which statement about Roth IRAs is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"Contributions are tax-deductible","B":"RMDs are required at age 73","C":"Qualified withdrawals are completely tax-free","D":"There is no income limit to contribute"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Roth IRA qualified withdrawals are completely tax-free. Contributions are NOT deductible, there are no RMDs for the original owner, and there ARE income limits for contributions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-008","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"When withdrawing from a Roth IRA, which comes out FIRST?","choices":{"A":"Earnings","B":"Conversion amounts","C":"Regular contributions","D":"The owner chooses"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Roth IRA withdrawals follow a specific order: (1) regular contributions first (always tax-free), (2) conversion amounts, (3) earnings. This ordering makes contributions accessible without tax or penalty anytime.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-009","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"ERISA applies to which of the following?","choices":{"A":"State government pension plans","B":"Church retirement plans","C":"Private employer 401(k) plans","D":"Traditional IRAs"},"answer":"C","explanation":"ERISA governs private sector employer retirement plans like 401(k)s. Government plans, church plans (if they elect exemption), and IRAs (not employer-sponsored) are NOT covered by ERISA.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-010","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"An ERISA fiduciary must act:","choices":{"A":"In the best interest of the employer","B":"Solely in the interest of plan participants","C":"To maximize returns regardless of risk","D":"According to their personal investment philosophy"},"answer":"B","explanation":"ERISA requires fiduciaries to act SOLELY in the interest of plan participants and beneficiaries. This duty of loyalty is the highest standard of care and prohibits any conflicts of interest.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-011","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"Under ERISA, a plan fiduciary who loans money from the plan to themselves has committed:","choices":{"A":"An acceptable transaction with proper documentation","B":"A minor violation requiring disclosure only","C":"A prohibited transaction","D":"An exempt transaction"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Borrowing from a retirement plan is a prohibited transaction under ERISA. Fiduciaries cannot use plan assets for their own benefit, regardless of intent to repay or documentation.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch9-012","section":"Federal Regulations","stem":"The prudent investor rule requires fiduciaries to:","choices":{"A":"Always select the highest-return investments","B":"Evaluate investments as part of the total portfolio and diversify","C":"Avoid all investments with any risk","D":"Invest only in government securities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The prudent investor rule requires evaluating investments in the context of the total portfolio and diversifying to minimize large loss risk. It focuses on the process and considers risk-return tradeoffs.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-001","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An investor sells stock at a loss on December 1 and purchases the same stock on December 15. Under the wash sale rule:","choices":{"A":"The loss is fully deductible in the current year","B":"The loss is disallowed and added to the cost basis of the new shares","C":"Only 50% of the loss is deductible","D":"The loss is deferred to the following tax year"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The wash sale rule disallows the loss if substantially identical securities are purchased within 30 days before or after the sale. The disallowed loss is added to the cost basis of the replacement shares.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-002","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A married couple filing jointly has $300,000 in wages and $50,000 in investment income. Their Net Investment Income Tax (NIIT) liability is:","choices":{"A":"$0 - They are below the threshold","B":"$1,900 (3.8% x $50,000)","C":"$3,800 (3.8% x $100,000)","D":"$11,400 (3.8% x $300,000)"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The NIIT threshold for married filing jointly is $250,000. Their MAGI is $350,000, which exceeds the threshold by $100,000. The NIIT is 3.8% on the LESSER of investment income ($50,000) or excess MAGI ($100,000), so 3.8% x $50,000 = $1,900.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-003","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"To receive qualified dividend treatment, an investor must hold the stock for at least:","choices":{"A":"30 days before the ex-dividend date","B":"60 days during the 121-day period around the ex-dividend date","C":"90 days before the record date","D":"1 year before receiving the dividend"},"answer":"B","explanation":"To qualify for preferential dividend tax rates, the investor must hold the stock for more than 60 days during the 121-day period beginning 60 days before the ex-dividend date.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-004","section":"Debt Securities","stem":"An investor in the 32% marginal tax bracket is considering a municipal bond yielding 4%. What is the tax-equivalent yield?","choices":{"A":"4.00%","B":"5.26%","C":"5.88%","D":"6.25%"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax-equivalent yield = Municipal yield / (1 - tax rate) = 4% / (1 - 0.32) = 4% / 0.68 = 5.88%. This means a taxable bond would need to yield 5.88% to match the after-tax return of the 4% muni.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["municipal-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An investor dies owning stock with a cost basis of $50,000 and a fair market value of $200,000. The heir sells the stock for $210,000. The taxable capital gain is:","choices":{"A":"$160,000","B":"$150,000","C":"$10,000","D":"$0"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The heir receives a stepped-up basis to the fair market value at death ($200,000). The taxable gain is the selling price ($210,000) minus the stepped-up basis ($200,000) = $10,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-006","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which of the following is NOT a probate asset?","choices":{"A":"Real estate owned solely by the decedent","B":"A brokerage account with a TOD designation","C":"Personal property in the decedent's name","D":"A bank account in the decedent's name only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A brokerage account with a Transfer-on-Death (TOD) designation passes directly to the named beneficiary outside of probate. The other assets would go through the probate process.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-007","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"In 2025, a married couple wants to give their daughter as much as possible without using any lifetime exemption. They may give up to:","choices":{"A":"$19,000","B":"$38,000","C":"$76,000","D":"Unlimited if for tuition paid directly"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Each spouse can give $19,000 per recipient using the annual exclusion. With gift splitting, a married couple can give $38,000 to one person without using any lifetime exemption.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-008","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which type of trust removes assets from the grantor's taxable estate?","choices":{"A":"Revocable living trust","B":"Testamentary trust","C":"Irrevocable trust","D":"Pour-over trust"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Only an irrevocable trust removes assets from the grantor's taxable estate because the grantor gives up control. Revocable trusts are included in the estate because the grantor retains control.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under SECURE 2.0, an individual can roll over 529 plan funds to a Roth IRA. Which requirement must be met?","choices":{"A":"The 529 account must be open for at least 10 years","B":"The rollover is subject to Roth IRA income limits","C":"The 529 account must be open for at least 15 years","D":"The annual rollover limit is $10,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The 529-to-Roth IRA rollover requires the 529 account to be open for at least 15 years. The rollover is NOT subject to Roth income limits, making it valuable for high earners.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Which account type offers a \"triple tax advantage\"?","choices":{"A":"529 Plan","B":"Coverdell ESA","C":"Health Savings Account (HSA)","D":"UTMA"},"answer":"C","explanation":"HSAs offer triple tax benefits: tax-deductible contributions, tax-free growth, and tax-free withdrawals for qualified medical expenses. No other account provides all three benefits.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A 16-year-old has $5,000 in unearned income from an UTMA account. Under the kiddie tax rules, how is this income taxed?","choices":{"A":"All at the child's rate","B":"All at the parent's rate","C":"$1,300 tax-free, $1,300 at child's rate, $2,400 at parent's rate","D":"$2,600 at child's rate, $2,400 at parent's rate"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under kiddie tax rules: first $1,300 is tax-free, next $1,300 is at child's rate, and the remaining $2,400 ($5,000 - $2,600) is taxed at the parent's marginal rate.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch10-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"What is the maximum HSA contribution for a family with two parents age 56 and 58 in 2025?","choices":{"A":"$8,550","B":"$9,550","C":"$10,550","D":"$11,550"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The 2025 family HSA limit is $8,550. Each spouse over 55 can add a $1,000 catch-up contribution. However, catch-up contributions must be made to separate HSAs. Total: $8,550 + $1,000 + $1,000 = $10,550.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["retirement-accounts"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-001","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A CPA prepares tax returns and occasionally recommends stocks to clients during their meetings. The CPA charges only for tax preparation. Is the CPA an investment adviser?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the CPA gives advice about securities","B":"Yes, because tax preparation fees are a form of compensation","C":"No, because advice is incidental to the accounting profession","D":"No, because the CPA is not in the business of giving advice"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The CPA qualifies for the LATE exclusion because investment advice is incidental to the accounting practice and no separate compensation is received for the advice.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-002","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following would cause a broker-dealer to lose its exclusion from the investment adviser definition?","choices":{"A":"Providing advice to retail customers","B":"Charging commissions on trades","C":"Receiving special compensation for advisory services","D":"Having registered representatives"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A broker-dealer is excluded from the IA definition if advice is incidental and no special compensation is received. Receiving special compensation for advisory services would cause them to lose the exclusion.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-003","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser has $95 million in AUM and a place of business in one state. The adviser:","choices":{"A":"Must register with the SEC","B":"Must register with the state","C":"May choose to register with either SEC or state","D":"Is exempt from registration"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Advisers with less than $100 million AUM must register with the state(s) where they have a place of business. They are not eligible for SEC registration unless an exception applies.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-004","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An adviser has no place of business in State A but has 7 clients there. The adviser:","choices":{"A":"Qualifies for the de minimis exemption","B":"Must register in State A","C":"May continue operating without registration for 30 days","D":"Is exempt because they have no office in the state"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The de minimis exemption requires 5 or fewer clients in a state (plus no place of business). With 7 clients, the adviser exceeds the threshold and must register in State A.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-005","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When must an investment adviser deliver its brochure (Form ADV Part 2A) to a new client?","choices":{"A":"30 days before signing the advisory contract","B":"Before or at the time of signing the advisory contract","C":"Within 5 business days of signing the contract","D":"Within 90 days of the fiscal year end"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The brochure must be delivered to clients before or at the time of entering into an advisory contract. This timing requirement applies even for oral agreements.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Form ADV Part 2B (brochure supplement) contains information about:","choices":{"A":"The firm's ownership structure","B":"The supervised persons who provide advice to clients","C":"Fee schedules and billing practices","D":"Conflicts of interest policies"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Part 2B is the brochure supplement that provides information about supervised persons who provide investment advice to clients, including their background and disciplinary history.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser must file a prompt amendment to Form ADV when:","choices":{"A":"A new client opens an account","B":"There is a change in disciplinary history","C":"Assets under management increase by 10%","D":"Annual registration renewal is due"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Material changes to an adviser's disciplinary history require prompt filing within 30 days. Regular AUM changes and new clients don't require immediate amendments.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-008","section":"State Regulations","stem":"How long must an investment adviser retain its books and records?","choices":{"A":"3 years, all at principal office","B":"5 years, first 2 years at principal office","C":"7 years, first 3 years at principal office","D":"10 years, all at accessible location"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Investment advisers must retain records for 5 years. The first 2 years must be at the principal office; years 3-5 can be at any accessible location.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-009","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which exam combination qualifies an individual as both a registered representative AND an investment adviser representative?","choices":{"A":"Series 65 only","B":"Series 66 only","C":"SIE, Series 7, and Series 66","D":"Series 63 and Series 65"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SIE + Series 7 qualifies as a registered representative, and Series 66 (with Series 7 as prerequisite) qualifies as an IAR. Together, they provide both qualifications.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-010","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An employee at an investment adviser firm schedules client meetings and processes account paperwork. This employee:","choices":{"A":"Must register as an IAR","B":"Is excluded from IAR registration as clerical","C":"Must pass the Series 65 exam","D":"Requires a professional designation waiver"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Employees who perform only clerical and ministerial functions (scheduling, paperwork processing) are excluded from the IAR definition and do not need to register.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-011","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which professional designation is most widely accepted as a waiver for the Series 65/66 exam requirement?","choices":{"A":"MBA (Master of Business Administration)","B":"CPA (Certified Public Accountant)","C":"CFA (Chartered Financial Analyst)","D":"JD (Juris Doctor)"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The CFA (Chartered Financial Analyst) designation is widely accepted by states as a waiver for the Series 65 or 66 exam requirement. MBA, CPA, and JD are not accepted for exam waivers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch11-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When an IAR terminates employment with an investment adviser, the former employer must:","choices":{"A":"File Form ADV-W within 30 days","B":"File Form U5 within 30 days","C":"File Form U4 within 30 days","D":"Notify the SEC within 5 business days"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When an IAR leaves a firm, the former employer must file Form U5 (Uniform Termination Notice) within 30 days. Form U4 is for initial registration; Form ADV-W is for adviser withdrawal.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-001","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When a broker-dealer sells securities from its own inventory to a customer, it is acting as:","choices":{"A":"An agent earning a commission","B":"A principal (dealer) earning a markup","C":"An investment adviser charging a fee","D":"A custodian holding securities"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When selling from its own inventory, a broker-dealer is acting as a DEALER (principal), not a broker. The compensation is a markup over the firm's cost, not a commission.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-002","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following is excluded from the definition of a broker-dealer?","choices":{"A":"A firm that executes customer orders","B":"An issuer selling its own securities","C":"A firm that makes markets in securities","D":"A firm that underwrites new issues"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An issuer selling its own securities is excluded from the broker-dealer definition. The issuer is not acting as an intermediary for others but is selling its own securities directly.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-003","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent of a broker-dealer may be associated with:","choices":{"A":"Multiple broker-dealers simultaneously","B":"Only one broker-dealer at a time","C":"A broker-dealer and an issuer simultaneously","D":"Any number of firms as independent contractor"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An agent may be associated with only one broker-dealer at a time. This ensures proper supervision and accountability for the agent's activities.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-004","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A location where a supervisor reviews and accepts customer orders is classified as:","choices":{"A":"A non-branch location","B":"A branch office","C":"An Office of Supervisory Jurisdiction (OSJ)","D":"A satellite office"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A location where customer orders are reviewed and accepted, or where training and supervision of registered persons occurs, qualifies as an Office of Supervisory Jurisdiction (OSJ).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-005","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A security listed on the New York Stock Exchange is:","choices":{"A":"Subject to full state registration by qualification","B":"A federal covered security requiring only notice filing","C":"Completely exempt from all state requirements","D":"Required to register by coordination"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Securities listed on national exchanges (NYSE, NASDAQ) are federal covered securities under NSMIA. States can only require notice filing, not full registration.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","securities-act-1934"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Registration by coordination becomes effective:","choices":{"A":"30 days after filing with the state","B":"When the state administrator approves","C":"At the same time as federal SEC registration","D":"Upon completion of the merit review"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Registration by coordination is designed to become effective simultaneously with the federal SEC registration, provided no stop order is pending and all state requirements are met.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following is an exempt SECURITY rather than an exempt transaction?","choices":{"A":"A private placement to accredited investors","B":"An unsolicited customer order","C":"A U.S. Treasury bond","D":"A sale to an institutional investor"},"answer":"C","explanation":"U.S. Treasury bonds are exempt securities - they are always exempt from registration regardless of the transaction. The other options are exempt transactions, where only that specific sale is exempt.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","government-bonds"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-008","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An issuer conducts a private placement under the state exemption. Two years later, one of the original purchasers wants to sell their shares. This subsequent sale:","choices":{"A":"Is automatically exempt as a private placement","B":"May require registration unless another exemption applies","C":"Is exempt because the original offering was exempt","D":"Is prohibited under state law"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Exempt transactions only exempt that specific sale. The original private placement was exempt, but the subsequent resale may require registration unless it qualifies for its own exemption (like an isolated non-issuer transaction).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-009","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The state Administrator may take which action WITHOUT providing prior notice or a hearing?","choices":{"A":"Revoke a registration","B":"Deny a registration application","C":"Issue a cease and desist order","D":"Cancel a registration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Cease and desist orders can be issued without prior notice to immediately stop ongoing or threatened violations. Denial, suspension, revocation, and cancellation all require notice and opportunity for a hearing.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-010","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investor purchases unregistered securities and later discovers the violation. The investor may bring a civil action within:","choices":{"A":"1 year from the sale","B":"2 years from the sale","C":"The earlier of 3 years from sale or 2 years from discovery","D":"5 years from the violation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The civil statute of limitations is the earlier of 3 years from the date of sale OR 2 years from discovery of the violation. The 5-year limit applies to criminal prosecutions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-011","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, the maximum criminal penalty for willful violation is:","choices":{"A":"Fine of $10,000 only","B":"Imprisonment for 5 years only","C":"Fine of $5,000 and/or imprisonment for 3 years","D":"Fine of $100,000 and/or imprisonment for 10 years"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The USA provides for maximum criminal penalties of a $5,000 fine and/or up to 3 years imprisonment for willful violations. Federal penalties under SEC rules are significantly higher.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch12-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A broker-dealer commits securities fraud in a transaction involving exempt securities. Which statement is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"The antifraud provisions do not apply to exempt securities","B":"The antifraud provisions apply to all securities transactions","C":"Only the SEC can enforce antifraud rules for exempt securities","D":"Exempt securities are exempt from all state regulation"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Antifraud provisions apply to ALL securities transactions, including those involving exempt securities, federal covered securities, and exempt transactions. There are no exemptions from antifraud rules.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-001","section":"Suitability","stem":"Under the SEC's fiduciary interpretation, an investment adviser's fiduciary duty consists of:","choices":{"A":"Duty of suitability only","B":"Duty of care and duty of loyalty","C":"Duty of disclosure only","D":"Duty of best execution only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The SEC's 2019 interpretation clarified that fiduciary duty has two main components: the duty of care (providing diligent, skillful advice) and the duty of loyalty (putting client interests first).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-002","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which statement about an investment adviser's fiduciary duty is TRUE?","choices":{"A":"The duty can be completely waived with client consent","B":"The duty applies only at the time of recommendation","C":"The duty cannot be entirely waived but can be shaped by contract","D":"The duty is identical to a broker-dealer's Reg BI obligation"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The SEC expressly stated that the federal fiduciary duty cannot be entirely waived. However, advisers and clients can shape their relationship by contract, provided there is full disclosure and informed consent.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-003","section":"Suitability","stem":"Regulation Best Interest (Reg BI) applies to:","choices":{"A":"Investment advisers only","B":"Broker-dealers making recommendations to retail customers","C":"Both investment advisers and broker-dealers equally","D":"Federal covered advisers only"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Reg BI applies to broker-dealers when making recommendations to retail customers. Investment advisers remain subject to the higher fiduciary standard under the Investment Advisers Act.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["reg-bi","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-004","section":"Suitability","stem":"The four component obligations of Regulation Best Interest are:","choices":{"A":"Suitability, Disclosure, Registration, and Supervision","B":"Disclosure, Care, Conflict of Interest, and Compliance","C":"Loyalty, Care, Best Execution, and Monitoring","D":"Transparency, Fairness, Competence, and Ethics"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Reg BI requires broker-dealers to satisfy four component obligations: Disclosure, Care, Conflict of Interest, and Compliance. Each must be met to satisfy the best interest standard.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["reg-bi","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-005","section":"Suitability","stem":"A broker's account has a turnover ratio of 6 and a cost-equity ratio of 22%. This suggests:","choices":{"A":"Normal trading activity for an active account","B":"Possible churning that requires investigation","C":"Indicators generally considered conclusive of churning","D":"Acceptable trading for a conservative investor"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A turnover ratio of 6 or higher and a cost-equity ratio above 20% are generally considered indicative of excessive trading/churning. These levels would warrant serious regulatory concern.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser may share in a client's profits and losses if:","choices":{"A":"It is never allowed under any circumstances","B":"There is written consent and sharing is proportionate to capital","C":"The client verbally agrees","D":"The adviser is a fiduciary"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sharing in profits/losses is allowed with written client consent, firm approval, and proportionate sharing based on capital contribution. The exception is for immediate family members where proportionate sharing is not required.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A broker tells a client, \"If you lose any money on this trade, I'll personally reimburse you.\" This statement:","choices":{"A":"Is acceptable if made in writing","B":"Is acceptable if the client is a qualified investor","C":"Is always prohibited as a guarantee against loss","D":"Is allowed if approved by the firm"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Guaranteeing against loss is absolutely prohibited regardless of circumstances. This includes promises to cover losses, guarantee returns, or make up losses from personal funds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-008","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An adviser learns a large institutional client will purchase 100,000 shares of XYZ. Before executing the client's order, the adviser buys XYZ for their personal account. This is:","choices":{"A":"Acceptable if disclosed to the client afterward","B":"Front-running, which is prohibited","C":"Allowed if the personal trade is small","D":"Permitted if the adviser believes it won't affect price"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Front-running is trading ahead of known client orders to profit from the expected price movement. This practice is strictly prohibited and violates the adviser's fiduciary duty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"An investment adviser has authority to deduct advisory fees directly from client accounts. Under the custody rule:","choices":{"A":"This does not constitute custody","B":"A surprise examination is required annually","C":"The adviser has custody but may be exempt from surprise examination","D":"The adviser must use a foreign financial institution"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Authority to deduct fees is considered custody. However, if the adviser has custody ONLY because of fee deduction authority, they may be exempt from the surprise examination requirement if other conditions are met.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the SEC custody rule, account statements must be sent to clients by:","choices":{"A":"The investment adviser","B":"The qualified custodian","C":"Either the adviser or custodian","D":"The SEC directly"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The qualified custodian must send account statements directly to clients at least quarterly. This is a critical protection ensuring clients receive independent verification of their holdings.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"When an investment adviser's affiliated company serves as the qualified custodian, the adviser must:","choices":{"A":"Obtain only a surprise examination","B":"Obtain only an internal control report","C":"Obtain both a surprise examination AND internal control report","D":"No additional requirements apply"},"answer":"C","explanation":"When the adviser or a related person serves as custodian, both an annual surprise examination AND an internal control report from an independent CPA are required. This provides enhanced protection when there is an affiliated relationship.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch13-012","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A state-registered investment adviser with custody of client assets typically must maintain a minimum net worth of:","choices":{"A":"$10,000","B":"$25,000","C":"$35,000","D":"$100,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"State-registered advisers with custody of client assets typically must maintain a minimum net worth of $35,000. Advisers with only discretionary authority (no custody) typically need $10,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-001","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the SEC Marketing Rule, investment adviser testimonials are:","choices":{"A":"Completely prohibited","B":"Allowed only for institutional clients","C":"Permitted with proper disclosures and oversight","D":"Allowed without any restrictions"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The 2022 SEC Marketing Rule permits testimonials with proper disclosures about compensation and conflicts, written agreements with promoters (unless de minimis), and firm oversight.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-002","section":"State Regulations","stem":"When advertising investment performance, an adviser must show returns for:","choices":{"A":"Only the most recent year","B":"Any time periods the adviser chooses","C":"1, 5, and 10-year periods (or since inception)","D":"Only periods where performance was positive"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The Marketing Rule requires showing 1, 5, and 10-year returns (or since inception if shorter) to prevent cherry-picking favorable time periods.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-003","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An adviser wants to show gross performance in an advertisement. Under the Marketing Rule:","choices":{"A":"Gross performance is prohibited","B":"Gross may be shown only if net performance is also shown","C":"Gross performance is preferred over net","D":"Gross is allowed only for institutional clients"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Marketing Rule allows gross performance to be shown ONLY IF net performance (after all fees and expenses) is also prominently displayed.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-004","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A written agreement with a promoter is required unless:","choices":{"A":"The promoter is a registered representative","B":"The promoter received less than $1,000 in the past 12 months","C":"The testimonial is posted on social media","D":"The adviser has less than $100 million AUM"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Written agreements with promoters are required except when the promoter is an affiliate of the adviser OR compensation is de minimis ($1,000 or less in the preceding 12 months).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-005","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Performance-based advisory fees may be charged to:","choices":{"A":"Any retail client who requests it","B":"Only institutional clients","C":"Qualified clients with $1.1 million AUM or $2.2 million net worth","D":"Any client who signs a performance fee agreement"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Performance-based fees are restricted to \"qualified clients\" who meet wealth thresholds: $1.1 million AUM with the adviser OR $2.2 million net worth (excluding primary residence).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-006","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser firm is being acquired. This acquisition:","choices":{"A":"Does not require client notification","B":"Is a deemed assignment requiring client consent","C":"Automatically terminates all client contracts","D":"Only affects new clients going forward"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A change in controlling interest of an investment adviser is deemed an \"assignment\" of client contracts. Clients must consent to the assignment and have the right to terminate without penalty.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-007","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which contract provision is prohibited?","choices":{"A":"\"Investment involves risk and past performance does not guarantee future results\"","B":"\"Client acknowledges understanding the investment strategy\"","C":"\"Adviser shall not be liable for losses resulting from its negligence\"","D":"\"Client may terminate this agreement with 30 days notice\""},"answer":"C","explanation":"Hedge clauses that attempt to waive liability for an adviser's negligence or violations of fiduciary duty are prohibited. General risk disclaimers are acceptable.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-008","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"A client pays a $6,000 quarterly fee in advance and terminates after one month. The client is entitled to a refund of:","choices":{"A":"$0 - prepaid fees are non-refundable","B":"$2,000","C":"$4,000","D":"$6,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Prepaid fees must be refunded on a pro-rata basis. The client paid for 3 months but only received 1 month of service, so they are entitled to 2/3 of the fee ($4,000).","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under Regulation S-P, an investment adviser must provide a privacy notice to clients:","choices":{"A":"Only at account opening","B":"At account opening and annually thereafter in all cases","C":"At account opening, with annual notice only if policies changed","D":"Only upon client request"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the 2024 amendments, initial privacy notice is required at account opening. Annual notices are no longer required if privacy policies haven't changed and information is only shared under opt-out exceptions.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Under the 2024 Regulation S-P amendments, breach notification must be sent:","choices":{"A":"Within 24 hours of discovery","B":"Within 30 days of discovery","C":"Within 60 days of discovery","D":"Only if the SEC requests it"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The 2024 amendments require covered institutions to provide timely notification to affected individuals within 30 days of discovering unauthorized access to sensitive customer information.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-011","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Large investment advisers with $1.5 billion or more in AUM must comply with the 2024 Reg S-P amendments by:","choices":{"A":"June 3, 2025","B":"December 3, 2025","C":"June 3, 2026","D":"December 3, 2026"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Large advisers with $1.5 billion or more in AUM have until December 3, 2025 to comply. Smaller advisers have until June 3, 2026.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch14-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Clients have the right to opt out of information sharing with:","choices":{"A":"All third parties including service providers","B":"Only government agencies","C":"Non-affiliated third parties (with certain exceptions)","D":"Only credit bureaus"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Clients have the right to opt out of information sharing with non-affiliated third parties. Exceptions exist for service providers, joint marketing arrangements, and legally required disclosures.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-001","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which type of suitability requires understanding that an investment is appropriate for at least some investors?","choices":{"A":"Customer-specific suitability","B":"Quantitative suitability","C":"Reasonable-basis suitability","D":"Fiduciary suitability"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Reasonable-basis suitability requires the representative to understand the investment and have a reasonable basis to believe it is suitable for at least some investors, before recommending it to anyone.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["suitability-rules","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-002","section":"Suitability","stem":"A customer places an unsolicited order for a speculative stock. The representative:","choices":{"A":"Must perform a full suitability analysis","B":"Should refuse the order if unsuitable","C":"May execute the order without a suitability determination","D":"Must have principal approval before execution"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Suitability requirements apply to recommendations, not unsolicited (customer-initiated) orders. The representative may execute an unsolicited order without performing a suitability analysis.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-003","section":"Suitability","stem":"Quantitative suitability is primarily designed to prevent:","choices":{"A":"Recommending unsuitable securities","B":"Opening inappropriate account types","C":"Excessive trading (churning)","D":"Insider trading"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Quantitative suitability addresses the amount of trading in an account. It is designed to prevent churning - excessive trading that generates commissions but doesn't benefit the customer.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["suitability-rules","finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-004","section":"Suitability","stem":"Which of the following is NOT typically part of a customer's investment profile?","choices":{"A":"Risk tolerance","B":"Investment time horizon","C":"Political affiliation","D":"Tax status"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Investment profile includes age, financial situation, tax status, risk tolerance, time horizon, and investment objectives. Political affiliation is not relevant to investment suitability.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["know-your-customer","suitability-rules"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-005","section":"Suitability","stem":"Best execution requires an adviser to seek:","choices":{"A":"The lowest commission rate available","B":"Execution only at national exchanges","C":"The most favorable terms reasonably available","D":"The fastest execution regardless of price"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Best execution requires seeking the most favorable terms reasonably available under the circumstances. This involves considering multiple factors including price, speed, size, and total cost - not just the lowest commission.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-006","section":"Suitability","stem":"Under Section 28(e), an investment adviser may use soft dollars to pay for:","choices":{"A":"Office rent and utilities","B":"Research reports and financial databases","C":"General accounting services","D":"Marketing and advertising"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Section 28(e) provides a safe harbor for soft dollar payments for research and brokerage services. Research reports and financial databases are eligible; office expenses and marketing are not.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-007","section":"Suitability","stem":"When aggregating trades for multiple client accounts, the adviser must:","choices":{"A":"Allocate based on account profitability","B":"Give priority to performance-fee accounts","C":"Allocate fairly and equitably among all accounts","D":"Allocate first to the largest accounts"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Trade allocation must be fair and equitable among all participating accounts. Advisers cannot favor accounts based on profitability, fee structure, or size.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-008","section":"Suitability","stem":"A client directs the adviser to use a specific broker. The adviser:","choices":{"A":"Must refuse if best execution cannot be achieved","B":"Must disclose the potential impact on execution quality","C":"Is fully responsible for execution quality","D":"Cannot accept directed brokerage arrangements"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When clients direct brokerage, the adviser must disclose that the client may not receive best execution. However, the adviser is not responsible for execution quality with client-directed brokerage.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["fiduciary-duty","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-009","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Discretionary trading authority requires:","choices":{"A":"Only verbal authorization from the client","B":"Written authorization from the client","C":"SEC approval","D":"Notarized documents"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Discretionary trading authority must be granted in writing by the client. Verbal authorization is not sufficient for discretionary accounts.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-010","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Before opening an options account, a customer must receive:","choices":{"A":"A copy of the firm's annual report","B":"The OCC Characteristics and Risks of Standardized Options","C":"FINRA's investor education materials","D":"A list of recommended options strategies"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The OCC's Characteristics and Risks of Standardized Options disclosure document must be delivered to customers at or before options account approval.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-011","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"For FINRA regulatory purposes, a customer complaint must be:","choices":{"A":"Made verbally to a supervisor","B":"Filed with FINRA directly","C":"In writing","D":"Notarized"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A regulatory complaint is defined as a written grievance. Verbal complaints, while they should be addressed, do not meet the formal definition of a complaint for FINRA recordkeeping purposes.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["finra"]},{"id":"series66-series66-ch15-012","section":"Customer Accounts","stem":"Time and price discretion over an order:","choices":{"A":"Requires full written discretionary authority","B":"Is the same as full discretionary authority","C":"Does not require written authorization","D":"Requires principal approval for each trade"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Time and price discretion (deciding when and at what price to execute an order) does not require written discretionary authorization. Full discretion over what securities to buy or sell does require written authorization.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["account-types"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-267","section":"Portfolio Management","stem":"A portfolio manager periodically adjusts holdings to return to the original target allocation after market movements. This practice is called:","choices":{"A":"Rebalancing","B":"Tactical asset allocation","C":"Dollar-cost averaging","D":"Sector rotation"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Rebalancing involves periodically adjusting a portfolio back to its target asset allocation after market movements cause drift. This maintains the original risk profile. Tactical allocation makes active bets on market conditions; dollar-cost averaging invests fixed amounts regularly; sector rotation shifts between industries.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["diversification"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-268","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent is registered in State A. While the agent's existing customer is temporarily vacationing in State B, the agent calls the customer and accepts an unsolicited order. The agent has no place of business in State B. Under the Uniform Securities Act, the agent:","choices":{"A":"Must register in State B before accepting the order","B":"Qualifies for the 'snowbird' exemption and need not register in State B","C":"May accept the order only if the broker-dealer registers in State B first","D":"Has committed a prohibited practice"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the NASAA 'snowbird' provision, an agent who is properly registered in the customer's home state may continue to service an EXISTING customer who is only temporarily present in another state, provided the agent has no place of business there. Because the customer's residence is unchanged, no registration in the visited state is triggered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-269","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, which of the following would be considered an EXEMPT transaction?","choices":{"A":"A solicited sale of a registered security to an individual retail investor","B":"An unsolicited order from a customer to buy a non-exempt security","C":"An agent recommending a private placement to 60 retail clients","D":"The sale of a new issue to the general public"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An unsolicited (non-solicited) customer order is an exempt transaction under the USA because the customer initiated it without the agent's recommendation. Exempt transactions remove the registration requirement for that particular sale, though antifraud provisions still apply.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-270","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the USA's private placement (limited offering) exemption, an offer of securities is exempt if directed to no more than how many non-institutional offerees in a 12-month period?","choices":{"A":"5","B":"10","C":"15","D":"35"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Uniform Securities Act limited offering (private placement) exemption permits offers to no more than 10 non-institutional (retail) offerees during any 12-month period. There is no numerical limit on offers to institutional investors. Note this differs from the federal Regulation D limit of 35 non-accredited purchasers.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["uniform-securities-act","exempt-transactions"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-271","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser directs client brokerage to a firm that charges slightly higher commissions in exchange for proprietary research the adviser uses in making investment decisions. This arrangement is permitted under:","choices":{"A":"The Section 28(e) soft-dollar safe harbor","B":"The agency cross transaction rule","C":"Regulation Best Interest","D":"The brochure rule"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Section 28(e) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 provides a safe harbor allowing an adviser to pay more than the lowest available commission in exchange for eligible brokerage and research services that lawfully assist the adviser's investment decision-making, so long as the commissions are reasonable in relation to the value received.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-272","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Which of the following items obtained with soft dollars would FALL OUTSIDE the Section 28(e) safe harbor?","choices":{"A":"Research reports and analyses","B":"Software used to analyze securities","C":"Payment of the adviser's office rent and overhead","D":"Seminars on portfolio strategy"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The 28(e) safe harbor covers eligible research and brokerage that assist the adviser's investment decision-making (research reports, analytic software, attendance at research seminars). Paying for office rent, overhead, computer hardware, travel, or salaries is NOT eligible and falls outside the safe harbor.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","fiduciary-duty"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-273","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A federal covered investment adviser that maintains custody of client funds and securities is generally required to engage an independent public accountant to conduct:","choices":{"A":"A monthly reconciliation filed with the SEC","B":"A surprise examination of client assets at least annually","C":"A quarterly audit of the adviser's net worth","D":"A semiannual review of the brochure"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Under the custody rule, an adviser with custody must (among other safeguards) undergo an annual SURPRISE examination by an independent public accountant to verify client assets, and client assets must be held by a qualified custodian that sends account statements directly to clients.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act","custody"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-274","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A wrap-fee program charges the client a single bundled fee for both advisory services and the execution of transactions. An adviser sponsoring a wrap-fee program must deliver to clients:","choices":{"A":"No disclosure document because the fee is bundled","B":"A specialized wrap-fee program brochure (Form ADV Part 2A, Appendix 1)","C":"Only a Form CRS","D":"A prospectus for each security purchased"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Sponsors of wrap-fee programs must deliver the specialized wrap-fee brochure, Form ADV Part 2A Appendix 1, which discloses the bundled fee, the services provided, and conflicts of interest. This replaces the standard Part 2A brochure for wrap clients.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-275","section":"State Regulations","stem":"As part of the registration process under the Uniform Securities Act, an applicant typically must file a consent to service of process, which:","choices":{"A":"Must be renewed and re-filed every year","B":"Appoints the Administrator as the applicant's agent to receive legal papers in noncriminal securities matters","C":"Waives the applicant's right to a hearing","D":"Authorizes the Administrator to manage client accounts"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A consent to service of process appoints the state Administrator as the applicant's attorney/agent to receive legal process (subpoenas, complaints) in noncriminal actions arising under the Act. It is filed once and remains in effect permanently; it need not be renewed annually.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-276","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, a registration of a broker-dealer, agent, or investment adviser, once effective, expires:","choices":{"A":"On the last day of December each year unless renewed","B":"Five years after it became effective","C":"Only when the registrant withdraws","D":"On the anniversary of the effective date"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Under the USA, registrations expire on December 31 each year unless renewed. Registrants must renew (and pay the renewal fee) annually to remain in good standing, regardless of when during the year they first registered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-277","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser representative (IAR) with no place of business in a state will NOT have to register in that state if, during the preceding 12 months, the IAR has had no more than:","choices":{"A":"1 client in that state","B":"5 retail clients in that state","C":"15 clients in that state","D":"35 accredited clients in that state"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The NASAA de minimis exemption permits an IAR (and an investment adviser) with no place of business in a state to avoid registration there if they have had 5 or fewer retail clients in that state during the preceding 12 months. Clients who are institutional or are existing clients who relocate are treated under separate rules.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-278","section":"State Regulations","stem":"The antifraud provisions of the Uniform Securities Act give the state Administrator jurisdiction over an offer to sell securities if the offer:","choices":{"A":"Originated in the state, was directed into the state, or was accepted in the state","B":"Only if both parties reside in the state","C":"Only if the security is registered in the state","D":"Only if the transaction is non-exempt"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The Administrator has jurisdiction over an offer that originates in the state, is directed into the state, or is accepted in the state. The antifraud authority reaches the transaction regardless of whether the security or transaction is exempt, so even exempt securities are covered.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-279","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An agent, without the broker-dealer's knowledge or approval, sells a private investment to a customer and collects compensation outside the firm. This prohibited practice is known as:","choices":{"A":"Churning","B":"Selling away","C":"Front running","D":"Backing away"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Selling away (private securities transactions) occurs when a registered person engages in securities transactions outside the scope of their employment without providing prior written notice to, and receiving approval from, the broker-dealer. It is a prohibited practice.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Easy","topics":["uniform-securities-act","prohibited-practices"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-280","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Uniform Securities Act, which of the following is NOT included in the definition of a 'security'?","choices":{"A":"A variable annuity","B":"A fixed annuity (guaranteed by the insurer)","C":"An investment contract","D":"A certificate of interest in an oil and gas program"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A fixed (guaranteed) annuity is an insurance product, not a security, because the insurer bears the investment risk. By contrast, variable annuities, investment contracts, and interests in oil-and-gas programs are securities because the purchaser bears investment risk.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-281","section":"State Regulations","stem":"Under the Investment Advisers Act of 1940, an advisory contract generally may NOT:","choices":{"A":"Disclose the fee schedule","B":"Be assigned to another adviser without the client's consent","C":"Describe the services to be provided","D":"State the contract's term"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An investment advisory contract may not be assigned to another adviser without the client's consent. It also must disclose that the adviser (if a partnership) will notify clients of any change in membership. Performance-based fees are restricted to qualified clients.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["investment-advisers-act"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-282","section":"State Regulations","stem":"A state Administrator may deny, suspend, or revoke a registration if it is in the public interest AND the applicant or registrant:","choices":{"A":"Earns a low income","B":"Was convicted of a securities-related misdemeanor within the past 10 years","C":"Does not hold a college degree","D":"Charges fees higher than competitors"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Statutory disqualifications under the USA include a felony conviction within the past 10 years (any felony) or a securities- or money-related misdemeanor within the past 10 years. The Administrator must also find that the action is in the public interest. Lack of a degree, low income, or higher fees are not statutory grounds.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Medium","topics":["uniform-securities-act","state-regulators"]},{"id":"series66-s66-q-283","section":"State Regulations","stem":"An investment adviser that takes custody of client funds must promptly notify the Administrator in writing, and (under state rules) must generally also meet a minimum net worth requirement of:","choices":{"A":"$5,000","B":"$10,000","C":"$35,000","D":"$100,000"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Under the NASAA model rule, a state-registered adviser with custody of client funds or securities must generally maintain minimum net worth of $35,000 (or post a bond). An adviser with discretion but no custody must maintain net worth of $10,000.","source":"OpenExamPrep.com (Series 66)","difficulty":"Hard","topics":["investment-advisers-act","custody"]}];
